"1177","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Chilton Foliat, Wiltshire, England":"Chilton Foliat, Wiltshire, England","Chilton Foliot, Wiltshire, England":"Chilton Manor, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Fritwell, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Fritwell, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Foliot","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian (Lombardy): variant of   Foglio  . This surname is very rare in Italy."],"variants":[{"name":"Foglio","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Carmine, Dino, Flavio, Julieta, Sal, Salvatore.","Italian: probably from the Latin personal name <i>Folius</i> (which is embodied in the common placename Fogliano)."]}]},{"name":"Samson","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name (Hebrew <i>Shimshon</i>, probably derived from <i>shemesh</i> ‘sun’), borne by a Jewish champion and judge famous for his prodigious strength. He was betrayed by his mistress, Delilah, and enslaved and blinded by the Philistines; nevertheless, he was able to bring the pillars of the temple of the Philistines crashing down in a final suicidal act of strength (Judges 13–16). This famous story provided the theme for  Milton's  poetic drama Samson Agonistes (  1671 ), which is modelled on ancient Greek tragedy. In the Middle Ages the popularity of the given name was increased in Celtic areas by the fame of a 6th-century Celtic saint who bore it, probably as a classicized form of some ancient Celtic name. He was a Welsh monk who did missionary work in Cornwall and afterwards established a monastery at Dol in Brittany."],"variants":[{"name":"Sampson","meanings":["The Greek form of the Scripture name, which Simonis translates, 'sol eximius,' i.e. illustrious sun; the Rev. A. Jones 'splendid sun,' i.e. great joy and felicity; Tregelles, ' solar, like the sun; ' and Fuerstius, ' sonnenahnlicher ' that is, one who resembles the sun (from shemesh, the sun)."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":2,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":11,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":46,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Samson Foliot was born in 1213, in Chilton Foliat, Wiltshire, England, his father, Henry Foliot, was 11210 and his mother, Lecia de Muntenei, was 35. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died on 30 May 1281, in Wiltshire, England, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1213–30 May 1281":"1213–30. mai 1281","1213–1281":"1213–1281","1237–1282":"1237–1282","1245–1285":"1245–1285","1177–1233":"1177–1233","1178–Female":"1178–Surnud","1285":"1285","1282":"1282","1281":"1281","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1237":"1237","1213":"1213","1202":"1202","1224":"1224","Bef 1233":"enne 1233","1245":"1245","30 May 1281":"30. mai 1281","1178":"1178","1233":"1233","1177":"1177","Wiltshire, Englan